# SDD Workflow — quick reference

This project uses a custom Spec-Driven Development workflow with three
personas (architect, developer, reviewer) coordinated through five slash
commands. Authoritative details live in `.cursor/commands/*.md`.

## Pipeline

```
/design feature-name
↓ (architect persona)
.cursor/specs/{feature}/
├── 00-global-spec.md
├── 00-technical-plan.md
├── tasks/NN-{layer}.md
└── status.md
↓
/build @.../tasks/NN-{layer}.md
↓ (developer persona — TDD)
status: ready for review
↓
/review
↓ (reviewer persona)
APPROVED → /build next task
CHANGES  → /build same task (fixing only flagged issues)
↓ (after all tasks done)
/review --commit (creates Conventional Commit)
```
## Commands

| Command | Persona | Effect |
|---------|---------|--------|
| `/design` | architect | Creates the four-file spec structure |
| `/build` | developer | Implements ONE task with TDD, stops |
| `/review` | reviewer | Audits last task, approves or returns issues |
| `/test` | none | Runs test suites independently |
| `/refactor` | none | Quality pass: phpcs + phpstan |

## Persona enforcement

The personas are NOT decorative. Each command starts by loading
`.cursor/skills/skill-{role}.md` and the model must operate within that
skill's boundaries:

- The architect does NOT write production code.
- The developer does NOT skip TDD or auto-advance to the next task.
- The reviewer does NOT modify source code.

Cross-persona pollution is the failure mode this workflow exists to prevent.

## Spec structure (mandatory)

Every feature spec lives at `.cursor/specs/{feature-name}/` with:

- `00-global-spec.md` — what & why (problem, criteria, edge cases)
- `00-technical-plan.md` — how (API contract, CQRS, structure, deps)
- `tasks/NN-{layer}.md` — single-commit mini-specs (≤ 2h each)
- `status.md` — progress tracker

Tasks are numbered by layer dependency:
01 Domain → 02 Application → 03 Infrastructure → 04 Integration.
Layers can be skipped or split (`02a-commands.md`, `02b-queries.md`).

## Architectural contract

All implementations follow the architectural contract in
`.cursor/rules/backend-standards.mdc`. The reviewer enforces it.

Infrastructure → Application → Domain
| Operation | Component | Returns |
|-----------|-----------|---------|
| Create | Command + Handler | `Uid` |
| Update / Delete | Command + Handler | `void` |
| Read | Query + Handler | DTO / `PaginationResults` |

## Test execution by layer

| Layer touched | Tests |
|---------------|-------|
| Domain | `composer tests` |
| Application | `composer tests` |
| Infrastructure | `composer tests` + `composer behat` |
| Controller / API | always `composer behat` |

Tests run inside the Docker container.

## Definition of Done (per task)

A task is done when `/review` returns APPROVED:
1. All acceptance criteria from the global spec covered
2. All implementation checklist items in the mini-spec completed
3. Tests for this layer green
4. `composer phpcs` clean, `composer phpstan` clean
5. Architectural checklist satisfied
6. `status.md` updated to `done`